There's no money in that.

218
00:13:33,500 --> 00:13:37,520
<i>Benny, you gotta come in
with us.</i>

219
00:13:37,600 --> 00:13:41,330
<i>- Who's "us"?
- "Who's us"? What are you so suspicious for?</i>

220
00:13:41,410 --> 00:13:43,340
You don't trust me?
It's me, Ray.

221
00:13:43,410 --> 00:13:46,100
- Remember my nickname in the joint?
- The Brain?

222
00:13:46,180 --> 00:13:49,110
The Brain. That's what
the guys used to call me. I got...

223
00:13:49,180 --> 00:13:51,580
But, Ray,
that was sarcastic.

224
00:13:51,650 --> 00:13:54,810
- That wasn't sarcastic, that was real.
- No, it was sarcastic.

225
00:13:54,890 --> 00:13:57,350
- There was nothing sarcastic about it!
- No, really, it was.

226
00:13:57,420 --> 00:14:01,790
- It was real. I was The Brain.
- No, it was sarcastic.

227
00:14:01,860 --> 00:14:04,160
- It wasn't sarcastic.
- Oh, my God!

228
00:14:04,230 --> 00:14:07,600
Oh, my God!
It was sarcastic!

229
00:14:09,300 --> 00:14:13,670
- Fellas, this is Benny. He's in.
- Benny? Looks like a cop to me.

230
00:14:13,740 --> 00:14:15,760
- How you doin'?
- Good. Nice to meet you.

231
00:14:15,840 --> 00:14:18,710
- You know you're workin' with a genius?
- I told him that.

232
00:14:18,780 --> 00:14:22,230
I mean, we're all smart,
but he wears glasses.

233
00:14:23,910 --> 00:14:26,540
- What's good? Pine, right?
- [Tommy] Oak.

234
00:14:26,620 --> 00:14:30,750
Redwood is what woodpeckers peck on.
It's the strongest.

235
00:14:30,820 --> 00:14:33,020
- That makes good trees, right?
- Yeah.

236
00:14:33,090 --> 00:14:35,680
This looks good.
This is good stuff.

237
00:14:35,760 --> 00:14:38,160
Look how long it is.
We could build a house with this.

238
00:14:38,230 --> 00:14:40,750
- We're just building a tunnel, right?
- Whoa, whoa.

239
00:14:40,830 --> 00:14:43,930
- Like a house. This is good stuff.
- A house, yeah.

240
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:46,060
How much is that?

241
00:14:46,140 --> 00:14:49,330
- A thousand bucks.
- A thousand bucks a box! Jesus!

242
00:14:49,410 --> 00:14:52,200
<i>- How many sticks in a box?
- Fifty.</i>

243
00:14:52,280 --> 00:14:56,740
<i>[Ray] My God, this is robbery.
This is unbelievable.</i>

244
00:14:56,810 --> 00:14:59,300
What do we need
all this dynamite for?

245
00:14:59,380 --> 00:15:02,280
What do we need the dynamite for?
Just be careful...

246
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:24,130
- Ahh.
- Can I have one of these and one of these?

247
00:15:24,210 --> 00:15:27,040
- Uh, okay. One of these?
- Mm-hmm.

248
00:15:27,110 --> 00:15:29,910
- One of these. Okay. You want a bag?
- No, that's okay.

249
00:15:29,980 --> 00:15:34,050
- I haven't got a bag. You'll take 'em like this?
- That's fine.

250
00:15:34,190 --> 00:15:36,090
<i>It's gonna be
a lot of work, fellas.</i>

251
00:15:36,160 --> 00:15:39,220
But when it's over, we're gonna
be all very well compensated.

252
00:15:39,290 --> 00:15:42,660
- Who's gonna work the drill?
- What do you mean?

253
00:15:42,730 --> 00:15:45,860
I don't know how
to work a drill like that.

254
00:15:45,930 --> 00:15:48,300
There's nothing to that.

255
00:15:48,370 --> 00:15:50,390
Whoever's gonna work the drill,
I'll tell you now,

256
00:15:50,470 --> 00:15:52,400
it's gonna make a lot of noise.

257
00:15:52,470 --> 00:15:55,270
No, no.
What do you think this is?

258
00:15:55,340 --> 00:15:58,830
This is why I get the big dough. We
wrap this blanket around it, it's fine.

259
00:15:58,910 --> 00:16:01,350
- You gotta know how to work a drill like that.
- [Drill Drilling]

260
00:16:01,420 --> 00:16:05,440
Whoa, take it easy.
Shut it off.

261
00:16:05,520 --> 00:16:09,250
<i>- [Drilling Noise Continues]
- [Men Shouting]</i>

262
00:16:09,320 --> 00:16:13,160
Will you guys shut up?
What did you do, tear a wall down?

263
00:16:13,230 --> 00:16:15,460
- We ain't started yet.
- What do you mean?

264
00:16:15,530 --> 00:16:18,000
What are you waiting for,
the drilling season?

265
00:16:18,070 --> 00:16:20,760
Do me a favor.
Go upstairs and bake.

266
00:16:20,830 --> 00:16:24,600
You know, I...
I don't need any help.

267
00:16:24,670 --> 00:16:27,640
<i>- [Denny] You got it?
- [Ray] No. You better brace me.</i>

268
00:16:27,710 --> 00:16:29,640
[Drilling Noise]

269
00:16:31,950 --> 00:16:34,440
Guys! What are you doing?

270
00:16:39,090 --> 00:16:41,710
Come on, get that thing!
Get that thing!

271
00:16:42,620 --> 00:16:46,020
You got it?
Okay, hold it.

272
00:16:52,530 --> 00:16:55,760
[Shouting]

273
00:16:58,410 --> 00:17:01,810
Could we have a half dozen
of the chocolate cinnamon?

274
00:17:01,880 --> 00:17:04,110
We're closed... for Easter.

275
00:17:04,180 --> 00:17:06,940
- That was three months ago.
- Greek Easter.

276
00:17:07,010 --> 00:17:10,140
- Well, that was two months ago.
- Chinese Easter! We're closed, okay?

277
00:17:10,220 --> 00:17:13,350
I'd like a cookie for my daughter.
Honey, what kind do you want?

278
00:17:13,420 --> 00:17:17,790
All right! Come on, have a cookie.
Sure, take a cookie.

279
00:17:17,860 --> 00:17:20,220
<i>- How you doin'?
- Oh, hi.</i>

280
00:17:20,290 --> 00:17:23,490
- You still open?
- Yeah, yeah, sure. Sure.

281
00:17:23,560 --> 00:17:27,020
- Give me two cherry cinnamon.
- Cherry cinnamon, right.

282
00:17:27,100 --> 00:17:29,690
- New here, huh?
- Just opened today, yeah.

283
00:17:29,770 --> 00:17:31,900
<i>- [Clanging Sounds]
- What's all that noise in the back?</i>

284
00:17:31,970 --> 00:17:35,840
Oh, that's the, uh, cookie press.
Needs oil, you know.

285
00:17:35,910 --> 00:17:39,710
- There's a slight leak.
- This is our plumber.

286
00:17:39,780 --> 00:17:42,310
- I'm the plumber. There's a tiny leak.
- How's it goin'?

287
00:17:42,380 --> 00:17:44,540
- What do I owe you?
- Oh, no charge.

288
00:17:44,620 --> 00:17:47,920
- Thanks a lot. Take it easy.
- I gotta get some sandbags.

289
00:17:47,990 --> 00:17:51,190
The cookies,
they're 85 cents.

290
00:17:51,260 --> 00:17:54,660
- Somebody get the sandbags.
- Just relax. You're a perfect fit.

291
00:17:54,730 --> 00:17:58,660
- Where the hell are the sandbags?
- Just relax!

292
00:17:59,900 --> 00:18:02,870
Okay, so we got off
to a shaky start.

293
00:18:02,940 --> 00:18:04,870
Yeah,
I'd say it was shaky.

294
00:18:04,940 --> 00:18:08,570
<i>There's gonna be glitches.
No question about it. So what?</i>

295
00:18:08,640 --> 00:18:10,770
Tomorrow
bring a bathing suit.

296
00:18:10,840 --> 00:18:14,540
<i>I'm not discouraged
'cause I don't get discouraged.</i>

297
00:18:14,610 --> 00:18:18,980
You know, there was a woman on before.
She's got over 200 pairs of shoes.

298
00:18:19,050 --> 00:18:22,250
<i>Don't worry. You're gonna get yours,
Frenchy. I promise you.</i>

299
00:18:22,320 --> 00:18:25,620
You're gonna be fine. This time,
a month or two, we'll be in Miami.

300
00:18:25,690 --> 00:18:27,630
It'll be great.

301
00:18:27,690 --> 00:18:30,490
A patron of the arts.
Doesn't that sound great?

302
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:32,830
- Frenchy...
- Opening night at the opera.

303
00:18:32,900 --> 00:18:35,330
I love you. Can I tell you this?
I love you.

304
00:18:35,400 --> 00:18:38,930
You know why? 'Cause you back me
all the time, you stand by me.

305
00:18:39,010 --> 00:18:41,170
You know when I first knew
I loved you?

306
00:18:41,240 --> 00:18:43,270
This was a long time ago.

307
00:18:43,340 --> 00:18:48,080
Remember I taught you how to open
a safe by moving the tumblers?

308
00:18:48,150 --> 00:18:50,080
And you got it.

309
00:18:50,150 --> 00:18:53,880
You're a very romantic man.
And I'm a lucky woman...

310
00:18:53,950 --> 00:18:57,010
because not many wives
get to see their husbands...

311
00:18:57,090 --> 00:18:59,020
battling a ruptured water main.

312
00:18:59,090 --> 00:19:01,650
- I'm crazy about you.
- Crazy about you, darling.

313
00:19:03,230 --> 00:19:06,360
- Here, Benny.
- Go ahead, put it in the bag.

314
00:19:06,430 --> 00:19:08,870
- I'll give it to you...
- he puts it in the bag!

315
00:19:08,940 --> 00:19:11,900
- Right, so it don't make no noise.
- This is efficiency.

316
00:19:11,970 --> 00:19:14,600
What the hell... What are you
putting it in his shovel for?

317
00:19:14,670 --> 00:19:17,140
- He puts it in the bag.
- It's call efficiency, my friend.

318
00:19:17,210 --> 00:19:20,480
- Teamwork.
- It saves energy.

319
00:19:20,550 --> 00:19:22,950
<i>- [Customers Chatting]
- I've got chocolate chip here.</i>

320
00:19:23,020 --> 00:19:25,250
I'll take a chocolate chip.

321
00:19:25,320 --> 00:19:28,150
<i>- The little girl was first. What do you want?
- Chocolate fudge.</i>

322
00:19:28,220 --> 00:19:30,490
Okay.
You can only have two.

323
00:19:30,560 --> 00:19:35,220
- What are you stopping for?
- I'm trying to figure this out.

324
00:19:35,300 --> 00:19:38,750
I think, according to this,
we're supposed to take a left turn.

325
00:19:38,830 --> 00:19:41,160
That doesn't mean stop.
Let's go.

326
00:19:41,230 --> 00:19:44,800
Will you give me...
What the hell are you doing?

327
00:19:44,870 --> 00:19:47,740
- What do you mean?
- You've got your hat on backwards.

328
00:19:47,810 --> 00:19:49,240
So?

329
00:19:49,310 --> 00:19:52,280
"So?" The flashlight
goes in the front.

330
00:19:52,350 --> 00:19:54,280
It looks cooler like this.

331
00:19:54,350 --> 00:19:56,650
Are you a jerk?
What do you mean it looks cooler?

332
00:19:56,720 --> 00:19:59,980
It's more stylish than that.
Look at that.

333
00:20:00,050 --> 00:20:02,420
- You think so?
- Yeah. Turn it around.

334
00:20:02,490 --> 00:20:06,260
This is chic like this.
Look at that. That's cool.

335
00:20:06,330 --> 00:20:09,730
- You got a mirror?
- I don't got a mirror. That looks good.

336
00:20:09,800 --> 00:20:13,130
- Look at yourself. I'll show you when we get out.
- All right.

337
00:20:13,200 --> 00:20:16,230
- Can you keep going?
- All right! I'm trying to figure the map out!

338
00:20:16,300 --> 00:20:18,900
One? Two?

339
00:20:18,970 --> 00:20:23,410
Okay, everybody, hold on.
That's $1.70. Thank you very much.

340
00:20:23,480 --> 00:20:27,810
- Thank you, thank you. Okay, yeah.
- [Customers Chattering]

341
00:20:27,880 --> 00:20:30,210
<i>[Tommy] What are you guys
gonna do with your share?</i>

342
00:20:30,280 --> 00:20:32,220
How much is my share?

343
00:20:32,290 --> 00:20:35,850
I figure it's gotta be
two million, right?

344
00:20:35,920 --> 00:20:38,120
I'm countin' the jewelry
in there too.

345
00:20:38,190 --> 00:20:42,630
<i>Then divided four ways,
that's a half million bucks apiece.</i>

346
00:20:42,700 --> 00:20:46,030
- What about Frenchy?
- What about Frenchy? She's just a front.

347
00:20:46,100 --> 00:20:48,030
But without Frenchy we're dead.

348
00:20:48,100 --> 00:20:51,200
We can get any broad
to sell cookies. Jeez.

349
00:20:51,270 --> 00:20:53,930
I say she gets a share,
but not a full share.

350
00:20:54,010 --> 00:20:55,980
I'd go for that.

351
00:20:56,040 --> 00:20:59,480
What if we each get a fourth
and she gets like a third?

352
00:20:59,550 --> 00:21:01,910
Are you nuts?
Then she'd be getting more than us.

353
00:21:01,980 --> 00:21:05,680
<i>- How do you figure?
- Where you gonna get four fourths and a third?</i>

354
00:21:05,750 --> 00:21:08,050
<i>- Can't you add?
- I don't do fractions.</i>

355
00:21:08,120 --> 00:21:11,750
Let's not get greedy. Remember
that movie with humphrey Bogart...

356
00:21:11,830 --> 00:21:13,950
when they're diggin'
for gold in the mountains?

357
00:21:14,030 --> 00:21:16,360
They find the gold
and they all get rich.

358
00:21:16,430 --> 00:21:19,960
Then this guy goes nuts and he turns on
his friends. Let's not let that happen here.

359
00:21:20,030 --> 00:21:22,730
Then he gets killed
by hispanics.

360
00:21:22,800 --> 00:21:25,360
<i>- What is it? The Treasure of...
- Treasure Island.</i>

361
00:21:25,440 --> 00:21:29,340
<i>- Treasure Island! That's right. That was a good movie.
- It was the best.</i>

362
00:21:29,410 --> 00:21:31,340
Okay, folks,
here's the deal.

363
00:21:31,410 --> 00:21:34,240
- I'm out of cookies, okay?
- [Customers Groaning]

364
00:21:34,310 --> 00:21:36,750
It's gonna be
like another two minutes,

365
00:21:36,820 --> 00:21:39,940
so that's the way
the cookie crumbles, okay?

366
00:21:40,020 --> 00:21:44,350
I got one cookie left.
You know who's gonna eat this? Me.

367
00:21:44,420 --> 00:21:47,260
<i>[Frenchy]
I gotta put on help.</i>

368
00:21:47,330 --> 00:21:50,820
<i>- Help?
- Yeah. I can't handle the volume.</i>

369
00:21:50,900 --> 00:21:54,060
A second person
you wanna put on?

370
00:21:54,130 --> 00:21:57,070
I can't help it, Ray.
The cookies are selling.

371
00:21:57,140 --> 00:22:02,800
Gee, I never counted on that.
You know, you gotta manage it somehow.

372
00:22:02,880 --> 00:22:05,900
What about my cousin May?
We can trust her.

373
00:22:05,980 --> 00:22:09,850
<i>May's a dodo. I'm gonna bring
a dodo into a master plan?</i>

374
00:22:09,920 --> 00:22:11,910
She's not a squealer.

375
00:22:11,990 --> 00:22:14,680
<i>She's not a squealer,
but then we'd have to cut her in.</i>

376
00:22:14,750 --> 00:22:17,020
<i>Meanwhile, the pot's getting
smaller and smaller.</i>

377
00:22:17,090 --> 00:22:20,290
I can't cook and sell
at the same time.

378
00:22:20,360 --> 00:22:23,190
It's a madhouse.
We'll get caught.

379
00:22:23,260 --> 00:22:26,460
Hey, wait a minute.
You know what we could do?

380
00:22:26,530 --> 00:22:30,630
We could hire May and
not tell her what we're doin'.

381
00:22:30,700 --> 00:22:35,160
'Cause she'll never catch on.
She's got, you know... And, and...

382
00:22:35,240 --> 00:22:39,040
- We're making enough dough from the cookies to pay her.
- Absolutely!

383
00:22:39,110 --> 00:22:43,140
We give her a small salary. She'll never
figure out or catch wise to anything.

384
00:22:43,220 --> 00:22:45,810
Because if you think
Denny and Tommy are slow,

385
00:22:45,890 --> 00:22:51,080
your cousin May is dumb
like a horse, or dog or something.

386
00:22:51,160 --> 00:22:53,390
Well, maybe it's not
such a great idea.

387
00:22:53,460 --> 00:22:56,500
No, I think we could do it.

388
00:22:56,630 --> 00:22:58,860
- Where are we? Right here?
- We're supposed to be here.

389
00:22:58,930 --> 00:23:01,870
<i>[May]
Excuse me. Where's the sugar?</i>

390
00:23:01,930 --> 00:23:03,900
Frenchy wants more sugar.

391
00:23:03,970 --> 00:23:08,030
May, stop bothering us.
We're busy.

392
00:23:08,110 --> 00:23:10,740
I just don't understand
about the drilling.

393
00:23:10,810 --> 00:23:14,870
I told you. Business is good.
We're expanding.

394
00:23:14,950 --> 00:23:17,510
We're expanding a little restaurant
and tea shop...

395
00:23:17,580 --> 00:23:20,350
so people could eat the cookies
and drink tea.

396
00:23:20,420 --> 00:23:23,910
Ah. Where are they gonna drink the tea?
In the tunnel?

397
00:23:23,990 --> 00:23:27,580
<i>I'd explain it to you,
but you gotta understand engineering.</i>

398
00:23:27,660 --> 00:23:30,930
- What's engineering?
- May, do me a favor, will you?

399
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:33,560
Business is good, we're expanding.
That's all you gotta know.

400
00:23:33,630 --> 00:23:36,570
How can you expand?
There's a nail shop next door.

401
00:23:36,640 --> 00:23:40,400
- We made a deal with them.
- So you're expanding into the nail shop.

402
00:23:40,470 --> 00:23:43,240
May, get your stuff.
You want the sugar?

403
00:23:43,310 --> 00:23:47,370
Take a hike.
Get the sugar and go. We'll call you.

404
00:23:47,450 --> 00:23:50,900
<i>- [Ray Sighs]
- [Tommy] This broad's big trouble. I'm tellin'you.</i>

405
00:23:50,980 --> 00:23:54,820
- You think it's safe having that strange broad here?
- Don't worry, she's harmless.

406
00:23:54,890 --> 00:23:57,820
I think we made a wrong turn. I don't
think we're still headed to the bank.

407
00:23:57,890 --> 00:24:02,050
- Please. Gimme the map.
- What are you talking about?

408
00:24:02,130 --> 00:24:04,620
For God's sakes.

409
00:24:04,700 --> 00:24:07,630
This is fine. I don't know what
you're all in a dither about.

410
00:24:07,700 --> 00:24:10,130
You're holding it
upside down.

411
00:24:10,200 --> 00:24:12,140
I am?

412
00:24:12,200 --> 00:24:15,200
You were reading this map
upside down all along?

413
00:24:15,270 --> 00:24:19,400
Get off my back! Can I help it
if they print these things like this?

414
00:24:19,550 --> 00:24:21,670
Okay.
Thank you very much.

415
00:24:21,750 --> 00:24:25,010
I gotta get another plate
of the cherry...

416
00:24:25,080 --> 00:24:28,380
- Can I help you? Next?
- I'm coming right back.

417
00:24:28,450 --> 00:24:31,180
<i>- [Policeman] Can I get two cherry cinnamon?
- Two cherry cinnamon.</i>

418
00:24:31,260 --> 00:24:33,660
- How you doin'?
- We're doing something right.

419
00:24:33,730 --> 00:24:35,990
- Next.
- Sure. Two cherry cinnamon.

420
00:24:36,060 --> 00:24:39,430
- You're new here, huh?
- Not really. This is my first day.

421
00:24:39,500 --> 00:24:42,330
Let me tell you something. These are
the greatest cookies I ever tasted.

422
00:24:42,400 --> 00:24:46,430
- Really? You know, we're expanding.
- No kiddin'?

423
00:24:46,510 --> 00:24:49,240
Yeah. There's some guys
in the back working now.

424
00:24:49,310 --> 00:24:51,900
- We got a tunnel under the nail shop.
- Really?

425
00:24:51,980 --> 00:24:54,380
- Yeah.
- Did you try the pecan fudge?

426
00:24:54,450 --> 00:24:57,940
- We were just talking about what an instant success this place is.
- Yes.

427
00:24:58,020 --> 00:25:00,950
- I was telling him about the restaurant.
- What restaurant?

428
00:25:01,020 --> 00:25:03,990
The tea room. You know, the guys in
the back tunneling for the tea room...

429
00:25:04,060 --> 00:25:07,290
- Under the nail shop?
- What are you talking about?

430
00:25:07,360 --> 00:25:10,660
- The tea room in the back.
- May, come and serve these people!

431
00:25:10,730 --> 00:25:14,320
We're at the Sunset Bake Shop
where the lines wait patiently...

432
00:25:14,400 --> 00:25:17,730
for what some people are calling the
most fabulous cookie treat in New York.

433
00:25:17,800 --> 00:25:19,740
What the hell is goin' on here?

434
00:25:19,810 --> 00:25:22,140
And you are the heart and soul
of Sunset Cookies.

435
00:25:22,210 --> 00:25:24,840
- Miss, uh...
- Frenchy Winkler.

436
00:25:24,910 --> 00:25:27,880
My real name's Frances
but everybody calls me Frenchy.

437
00:25:27,950 --> 00:25:30,040
As one stands here,
one can inhale the aroma...

438
00:25:30,120 --> 00:25:31,950
My God!
[Laughing]

439
00:25:32,020 --> 00:25:36,580
Of hot chocolate, cinnamon, fresh cherries
and a dozen other mouthwatering taste treats.

440
00:25:36,660 --> 00:25:41,020
Is it true customers wait on line
for half an hour for a single cookie?

441
00:25:41,090 --> 00:25:44,690
- That you've had to ration sales?
- Yeah, it happened like once.

442
00:25:44,760 --> 00:25:47,360
But what're you making
all the fuss about?

443
00:25:47,430 --> 00:25:50,300
Tell us. Where did you learn
the rare secret of your baking?

444
00:25:50,370 --> 00:25:52,670
Well, I don't know.
It's the only thing I can cook.

445
00:25:52,740 --> 00:25:55,670
- That and linguini with turkey meatballs.
- [Laughing]

446
00:25:55,740 --> 00:25:58,800
Sir, how would you describe
your cookie?

447
00:25:58,880 --> 00:26:02,370
Oh, I don't know.
It's baked with nutmeg or something.

448
00:26:02,450 --> 00:26:06,750
<i>- I just know it's great.
- And I just want to say that we're expanding.</i>

449
00:26:06,820 --> 00:26:10,080
- There are men in the back now tunneling...
- No, no, May! Get back...

450
00:26:10,160 --> 00:26:15,220
<i>I can't take this, Frenchy.
We don't want this kind of attention.</i>

451
00:26:15,290 --> 00:26:18,790
<i>Don't look at me! I didn't hire
a publicity agent. They just showed up!</i>

452
00:26:18,860 --> 00:26:21,560
I know, but it's really
putting us in the toilet.

453
00:26:21,630 --> 00:26:25,570
I can't concentrate. There's people
up there. Demanding cookies every day.

454
00:26:25,640 --> 00:26:29,540
And today Denny got bit by a rat.
We had to give him rabies shots.

455
00:26:29,610 --> 00:26:32,240
- Who, the rat?
- Very funny. You should be on TV.

456
00:26:32,310 --> 00:26:34,710
I am! Open your eyes!

457
00:26:34,780 --> 00:26:38,980
- Frenchy, I don't like this.
- Come on! You've been digging for weeks!

458
00:26:39,050 --> 00:26:41,540
When you gonna get somewhere?
How much longer is it gonna take?

459
00:26:41,620 --> 00:26:44,680
It's complicated!
We keep getting lost.

460
00:26:44,760 --> 00:26:47,220
The other day I was deep
in the tunnel, my hat went out.

461
00:26:47,290 --> 00:26:49,590
- That stupid coal miner's hat?
- That's right.

462
00:26:49,660 --> 00:26:52,190
It's a lifesaver, that hat.
That bulb.

463
00:26:52,260 --> 00:26:56,830
We'd have done better just with
a cookie store. We're making good dough.

464
00:26:56,900 --> 00:27:00,500
"Making good dough. " It's
a cookie store, but we're making dough.

465
00:27:00,570 --> 00:27:02,970
That's very... It's a cookie store.
We're making dough...

466
00:27:03,040 --> 00:27:05,240
I get it, I get it.

467
00:27:35,540 --> 00:27:38,870
[Benny] I knew we were going
the wrong way. I knew it!

468
00:27:38,940 --> 00:27:41,970
- What the hell we doin' in a dress shop?
- Your fault, you got the maps.

469
00:27:42,050 --> 00:27:44,950
At least it's a Sunday. We can
patch this up and get out of here.

470
00:27:45,020 --> 00:27:47,650
- How we gonna patch it up?
- We tile it and we get out.

471
00:27:47,720 --> 00:27:49,910
- Hello! I'm not a tiler.
- We don't have any tiles.

472
00:27:49,990 --> 00:27:52,650
Where do you get cement
in the middle of a dress shop?

473
00:27:52,720 --> 00:27:57,060
<i>Besides, Brain, how are we going
to close the hole and tile it?</i>

474
00:27:57,130 --> 00:28:00,830
We're inside the store.
How do we get out?

475
00:28:00,900 --> 00:28:04,530
Well, you tile... he's got a point.
You can't tile this from the other side.

476
00:28:04,600 --> 00:28:06,540
- No kidding.
- No, you can't.

477
00:28:06,610 --> 00:28:09,130
This is very discouraging, guys.

478
00:28:09,210 --> 00:28:12,470
<i>- I'm ready to pack this in.
- Everybody freeze!</i>

479
00:28:14,450 --> 00:28:19,320
Hey, Ray, your wife's cousin
talks too much.

480
00:28:19,380 --> 00:28:21,650
Sorry to spoil
your expansion plans, fellas.

481
00:28:21,720 --> 00:28:23,650
<i>[Ray]
Officer, listen to me.</i>

482
00:28:23,720 --> 00:28:28,130
We didn't do anything yet. Yes,
it's true, we were gonna rob the bank.

483
00:28:28,190 --> 00:28:32,130
But we screwed up everything,
except for the cookie shop.

484
00:28:32,200 --> 00:28:35,720
The cookie shop's doing great
for some reason. You like the cookies.

485
00:28:35,800 --> 00:28:40,530
Let us forget everything we were gonna
do and concentrate on the cookie store.

486
00:28:40,610 --> 00:28:44,470
Look, I'm not here trying to ruin
anybody's life, okay?

487
00:28:44,540 --> 00:28:46,740
Then give us a break.

488
00:28:46,810 --> 00:28:49,580
Think I could get
a little piece of the action?

489
00:28:49,650 --> 00:28:52,480
Yeah. I'm not opposed
to paying off the cops.

490
00:28:52,550 --> 00:28:54,540
It's a standard
business expense.

491
00:28:54,620 --> 00:28:57,780
<i>That's the thing. I don't want you
to think of it as a payoff.</i>

492
00:28:57,860 --> 00:29:00,590
<i>I think I'm qualified
to make what I believe...</i>

493
00:29:00,660 --> 00:29:03,290
is a major contribution
to this enterprise.

494
00:29:03,360 --> 00:29:05,560
My brother-in-law
majored in business.

495
00:29:05,630 --> 00:29:07,830
Let us hear this contribution,
all right?

496
00:29:07,900 --> 00:29:12,100
- One word.
- Yeah? And that word is?

497
00:29:13,370 --> 00:29:15,310
Franchise.

498
00:29:22,890 --> 00:29:24,890
<i>[Ray]
We got about 600 trucks.</i>

499
00:29:24,960 --> 00:29:30,300
<i>And, you know,
we're all over the country, and Canada.</i>

500
00:29:30,370 --> 00:29:34,430
<i>We make a lot of different cookies. Whatever
you want. We got pistachio, pretzels.</i>

501
00:29:34,510 --> 00:29:38,600
<i>We make chicken chip cookies,
tuna mint.</i>

502
00:29:38,680 --> 00:29:41,580
<i>[TVNewsman] Virtually overnight,
the Winklers and their associates...</i>

503
00:29:41,650 --> 00:29:45,550
<i>have gone from a small, modest
mom and pop cookie shop...</i>

504
00:29:45,620 --> 00:29:48,240
<i>to something approaching
a baking empire.</i>

505
00:29:48,320 --> 00:29:51,290
This is where
we package everything.

506
00:29:51,360 --> 00:29:54,020
And what we do is...

507
00:29:54,090 --> 00:29:57,460
The cookies have
a wonderful smell, a fresh smell.

508
00:29:57,530 --> 00:30:01,260
And that's all put on with
a chemical spray. We do that over here.

509
00:30:01,330 --> 00:30:04,360
There's no denying that he's
refreshingly down to Earth...

510
00:30:04,440 --> 00:30:06,490
for a corporate executive.

511
00:30:06,570 --> 00:30:08,700
So offbeat, in fact,
that Sunset Farms...

512
00:30:08,770 --> 00:30:12,400
has captured the imagination
of the public and the industry.

513
00:30:12,480 --> 00:30:14,910
We wanted to find out
what the competition thinks.

514
00:30:14,980 --> 00:30:18,310
So we went to Paul Milton
of American Cookies.

515
00:30:18,380 --> 00:30:21,320
The bottom line is,
they make a really great product.

516
00:30:21,390 --> 00:30:25,380
You have what the public wants, and
everything else takes care of itself.

517
00:30:25,460 --> 00:30:29,220
- This is your office?
- This is pretty much where I operate.

518
00:30:29,290 --> 00:30:31,820
Frenchy decorated this place.
You can tell.

519
00:30:31,900 --> 00:30:34,630
She's got, uh,
all her stuff here.

520
00:30:34,700 --> 00:30:37,830
This is an antique,
you know.

521
00:30:37,900 --> 00:30:42,270
She says it's, like,
Louis XIV or Louis XV.

522
00:30:42,340 --> 00:30:45,830
It's, uh... I don't know how high
the Louises go, actually.

523
00:30:45,910 --> 00:30:48,900
But it's a top Louis.
It's one of the...

524
00:30:48,980 --> 00:30:53,540
Frenchy stuck a TV in it,
you know, because she's got a creative...

525
00:30:53,620 --> 00:30:56,180
- She's a creative decorator.
- It's very original.

526
00:30:56,250 --> 00:31:00,310
- Um, how much are you worth?
- Oh, plenty, plenty.

527
00:31:00,390 --> 00:31:03,160
- I mean, how much? Just between you and me.
- A lot.

528
00:31:03,230 --> 00:31:06,530
We're worth a lot of dough.
Whatever you see is antiques.

529
00:31:06,600 --> 00:31:09,070
This thing here.
This if from...

530
00:31:09,130 --> 00:31:12,800
I don't remember exactly. It think it's the
Renaissance or the Magna Carta or something.

531
00:31:12,870 --> 00:31:14,800
But that's where it's from.

532
00:31:14,870 --> 00:31:18,000
Why did you decide to go
into baking so late in life?

533
00:31:18,080 --> 00:31:21,370
Well, Frenchy, we found out,
can make cookies.

534
00:31:21,450 --> 00:31:23,380
<i>[Newsman]
The Frenchy they're talking about,</i>

535
00:31:23,450 --> 00:31:26,080
<i>- and reigning culinary genius of Sunset,
- hello.</i>

536
00:31:26,150 --> 00:31:29,920
<i>Is Frances Fox, who happens
to be the wife of the C.E. O.</i>

537
00:31:29,990 --> 00:31:31,920
<i>So you made cookies
your whole life,</i>

538
00:31:31,990 --> 00:31:34,360
<i>and everybody told you
how delicious they were.</i>

539
00:31:34,430 --> 00:31:37,120
<i>- Yeah. I thought they were "B.S. Ing" me, you know?
- Really?</i>

540
00:31:37,190 --> 00:31:40,990
Yeah. Somebody gives you something they
cooked, you always say you enjoyed it...

541
00:31:41,070 --> 00:31:45,300
even if it makes you throw up
afterwards, so, you know...

542
00:31:45,370 --> 00:31:48,930
In a day and age where everyone seems
to have public relations handlers,

543
00:31:49,010 --> 00:31:51,270
it's hard to imagine
a corporate brain trust...

544
00:31:51,340 --> 00:31:55,610
that is more direct and less image conscious
than the group here at Sunset Farms.

545
00:31:55,680 --> 00:31:59,620
In fact, each person we met seemed
to be more eccentric than the last.

546
00:31:59,680 --> 00:32:01,810
Like Tommy Walker,
the chairman of the board.

547
00:32:01,890 --> 00:32:05,790
Frenchy makes the best cookies in the
world. We're very proud of her cookies.

548
00:32:05,860 --> 00:32:08,480
<i>What are your duties
as chairman of the board?</i>

549
00:32:08,560 --> 00:32:13,000
The board meets once or twice a week,
and we take up important issues.

550
00:32:13,060 --> 00:32:15,230
<i>- Issues?
- Yeah. Facts, problems.</i>

551
00:32:15,300 --> 00:32:17,230
Things like that.
Normal stuff.

552
00:32:17,300 --> 00:32:20,960
What kind of problems does an overnight
success like Sunset Farms face?

553
00:32:21,040 --> 00:32:24,970
What kind of problems? Last week the
toilet on the fourth floor wouldn't flush.

554
00:32:25,040 --> 00:32:28,100
It flushed, but the water
kept coming to the top.

555
00:32:28,180 --> 00:32:31,010
So the board voted
on getting a plumber.

556
00:32:31,080 --> 00:32:35,450
One of the architects of Sunset Farms's
unorthodox marketing strategy...

557
00:32:35,520 --> 00:32:39,580
is the head of advertising, Denny Doyle,
a former truck driver.

558
00:32:39,660 --> 00:32:42,630
Was it you who came up with
the idea to advertise baked goods...

559
00:32:42,690 --> 00:32:45,090
<i>in Playboy, Penthouse
and Hustler Magazine?</i>

560
00:32:45,160 --> 00:32:48,560
I figured if a guy's staring
at a naked piece of tail,

561
00:32:48,630 --> 00:32:51,860
and he sees the breasts and legs,
he's gonna start to salivate.

562
00:32:51,940 --> 00:32:54,460
It's human nature.
So if he's salivating,

563
00:32:54,540 --> 00:32:56,700
he turns the page and
comes across a picture of, say,

564
00:32:56,770 --> 00:32:58,710
our pistachio cream cookies.

565
00:32:58,780 --> 00:33:01,900
He thinks maybe that's why
he's drooling. You understand?

566
00:33:01,980 --> 00:33:03,910
It's psychology.
It's science.

567
00:33:03,980 --> 00:33:08,150
It's like Pablo's Theory, you know,
with the dog when he feeds him?

568
00:33:08,220 --> 00:33:10,850
<i>- Pablo?
- Pablo, with the dogs.</i>

569
00:33:10,920 --> 00:33:13,520
<i>[Newsman] Then there's
ex-police officer Ken Deloach,</i>

570
00:33:13,590 --> 00:33:16,390
<i>vice president
in charge of distribution.</i>

571
00:33:16,460 --> 00:33:20,490
<i>And Benjamin Borkowski, vice president
in charge of plant safety.</i>

572
00:33:20,560 --> 00:33:23,660
First thing I did was make sure
the building was fireproof.

573
00:33:23,730 --> 00:33:27,170
<i>[Newsman] And lest they be accused
of being a mostly male club,</i>

574
00:33:27,240 --> 00:33:31,680
<i>May Sloan is in charge of public
relations and also physical therapy.</i>

575
00:33:31,740 --> 00:33:34,140
<i>I understand
public relations.</i>

576
00:33:34,210 --> 00:33:36,510
<i>But physical therapy?</i>

577
00:33:36,580 --> 00:33:39,610
All the chocolate chips
are put in the cookies by hand.

578
00:33:39,680 --> 00:33:45,020
And that's really hard on the back
and leg muscles. I do deep massage.

579
00:33:45,090 --> 00:33:48,180
By the way,
she's also a vice president.

580
00:33:48,260 --> 00:33:51,130
So there you have it. A brief glimpse
into a corporate culture...

581
00:33:51,200 --> 00:33:54,650
that has industry leaders and management
analysts all over the country...

582
00:33:54,730 --> 00:33:59,670
scratching their heads, trying to figure
out what Sunset Farms might try next.

583
00:33:59,740 --> 00:34:04,470
It may be as simple as what Paul Milton,
the Winklers' chief competitor said:

584
00:34:04,540 --> 00:34:07,240
"If you've got something
the American public wants,

585
00:34:07,310 --> 00:34:09,440
everything else
falls into place. "

586
00:34:09,510 --> 00:34:11,780
Or as we in television
might say,

587
00:34:11,850 --> 00:34:14,410
"There's no accounting
for the public's taste. "

588
00:34:21,030 --> 00:34:23,820
Okay, keep coming through
with this stuff.

589
00:34:23,890 --> 00:34:25,830
It's better the way I had it.

590
00:34:25,900 --> 00:34:28,520
Darling, could you put the doll
by the ceramic zebra?

591
00:34:28,600 --> 00:34:30,530
<i>- [Man] Mrs. Winkler? Excuse me.
- Yes?</i>

592
00:34:30,600 --> 00:34:32,540
<i>- You wanted to check the menu.
- Right.</i>

593
00:34:32,600 --> 00:34:35,630
Stevens, could you bring that piece
downstairs that Mr. Winkler hates?

594
00:34:35,710 --> 00:34:37,940
Try it again
next to the fireplace.

595
00:34:38,010 --> 00:34:40,440
I want a lot of nuts
and "crude-ites. "

596
00:34:40,510 --> 00:34:43,310
What did we say for openers?
Oh, yes. Snails.

597
00:34:43,380 --> 00:34:46,320
Escargots, yes.
Then the potato and truffle salad.

598
00:34:46,380 --> 00:34:49,440
Yes. Truffles, by all means.
But I hate those thin pieces.

599
00:34:49,520 --> 00:34:52,490
When you shave it, go, go.
Lay it on big time.

600
00:34:52,560 --> 00:34:55,420
Truffles are always shaved
really finely.

601
00:34:55,490 --> 00:34:58,480
<i>- Naturally, I didn't mean to suggest anything overdone.
- Right.</i>

602
00:34:58,560 --> 00:35:01,400
<i>[Chef] Then we have
poached sea bass in phyllo.</i>

603
00:35:01,470 --> 00:35:05,160
<i>And spinach souffle,
and salad, and dessert.</i>

604
00:35:05,240 --> 00:35:09,170
- Oh, and finger bowls.
- There's nothing being served that requires finger bowls.

605
00:35:09,240 --> 00:35:12,900
Well have 'em, 'cause you can never predict
whose fingers will need a washing. Okay?

606
00:35:12,980 --> 00:35:16,610
<i>- Did you rearrange this place again?
- All right, hold your water.</i>

607
00:35:16,680 --> 00:35:18,610
Don't tell me to hold my water.

608
00:35:18,680 --> 00:35:20,840
Every night it's like walking
into a strange house.

609
00:35:20,920 --> 00:35:23,440
What is this thing?
Did I tell you to get rid of this?

610
00:35:23,520 --> 00:35:26,010
It's a harp.
You got no flair, Ray.

611
00:35:26,090 --> 00:35:28,920
Don't tell me I got no flair.
Nobody plays the harp.

612
00:35:28,990 --> 00:35:31,330
What's it doing in
the middle of the living room?

613
00:35:31,400 --> 00:35:33,730
I like the visual sweep.

614
00:35:33,800 --> 00:35:36,820
I don't know what's
gotten into your head.

615
00:35:36,900 --> 00:35:38,840
You're so hoity-toity
all of a sudden.

616
00:35:38,900 --> 00:35:42,810
My cookies pay for this,
so turn it off.

617
00:35:42,870 --> 00:35:44,810
What's for dinner?

618
00:35:44,880 --> 00:35:48,140
And don't tell me it's sparrows
on a bed of lettuce again.

619
00:35:48,210 --> 00:35:51,010
'Cause I wouldn't care if I had anything
on a bed of lettuce anymore.

620
00:35:51,080 --> 00:35:54,480
- They're pheasants, and you ate 'em last week.
- And I got BB's.

621
00:35:54,550 --> 00:35:57,380
Remember I got BB's in the mouth?
I almost choked on a BB.

622
00:35:57,450 --> 00:36:00,150
Can I get a cheeseburger?
Is that possible?

623
00:36:00,220 --> 00:36:02,160
It's the dinner party tonight!

624
00:36:02,230 --> 00:36:04,960
Oh! Great!

625
00:36:05,030 --> 00:36:08,050
- Just when I got a lot on my mind.
- Your mind don't hold a lot.

626
00:36:08,180 --> 00:36:10,670
Get dressed.
And don't forget, it's tuxedo.

627
00:36:10,750 --> 00:36:14,710
- I'm hungry. I don't wanna get dressed now.
- You want a snail?

628
00:36:14,790 --> 00:36:17,150
You nuts?
I'm gonna have a snail?

629
00:36:17,220 --> 00:36:19,190
Come on! You eat steamers.

630
00:36:19,260 --> 00:36:23,190
A snail leaves a trail of scum
in the yard when it walks.

631
00:36:23,260 --> 00:36:25,820
- Not in France they don't.
- Oh, Jesus.

632
00:36:25,900 --> 00:36:30,060
What happened to the turkey meatballs
and spaghetti? That's what I like.

633
00:36:30,140 --> 00:36:34,270
Have a potato and truffle thing.
That'll hold you till the company comes.

634
00:36:34,340 --> 00:36:37,330
I don't want truffles.
Truffles got no flavor!

635
00:36:37,410 --> 00:36:40,810
They're subtle.
Only pigs can find them.

636
00:36:40,880 --> 00:36:44,040
You're thinking of pearls. They come
in oysters. That's what that is.

637
00:36:44,120 --> 00:36:46,050
<i>Take a hike.</i>

638
00:36:46,120 --> 00:36:49,090
You're such an ignoramus.
That's what I love about you.

639
00:36:49,160 --> 00:36:52,780
- Pearls come in oysters.
- Ray, Ray, Ray.

640
00:36:52,860 --> 00:36:57,060
- Please, don't spoil my big night.
- What's so big about tonight?

641
00:36:57,130 --> 00:36:59,060
There's important people
coming from the arts,

642
00:36:59,130 --> 00:37:00,830
and I want to get on
some of those boards.

643
00:37:00,900 --> 00:37:03,770
Hey, we donate,
you'll be on the boards.

644
00:37:03,840 --> 00:37:07,800
- But I wanna be a patron.
- What you wanna be is a socialite.

645
00:37:07,870 --> 00:37:10,270
<i>So what?
Is that so terrible?</i>

646
00:37:10,340 --> 00:37:13,540
You know, when we talked about
making it, we were gonna hit it big,

647
